{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> εὐρύς</b>, εὐρεῖα, εὐρύ, <br /> <i>Ionic dialect</i> <i>feminine</i> εὐρέᾰ (not εὐρέη) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.178, compare 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 7.78 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <i>Aeolic dialect</i> <i>feminine</i> εὔρηα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 7th-6th c.BC: Alcaeus Lyricus “Supp.” 12.5 \">Refs 7th c.BC+</a>]: <i>genitive</i> εὐρέος, είας, έος: <i>accusative</i> <i>singular</i> εὐρύν, (in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus) sometimes εὐρέᾰ (see. below): _genitive_ εὐρέος as _feminine_, 7th-6th c.BC: Asius Lyricus 13, 3rd c.AD: Oppianus Apamensis Epicus “Cynegetica” 3.323: so _nominative_ _plural_ εὐρέες “Anthologia Graeca” 9.413 (1st c.AD: Antiphilus Epigrammaticus)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]:—<b>wide, broad</b>, οὐρανὸν εὐρύν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 3.364, +others; εὐρεῖα χθών 4.182, +others; εὐρέα πόντον 6.291; εὐρέα κόλπον 18.140, +others; εὐ. σχεδίη 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 5.163; ὦμοι 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 3.210, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 18.68, +others\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] (<i>comparative</i> εὐρύτερος δ᾽ ὤμοισιν ἰδὲ στέρνοισιν ἰδέσθαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 3.194); μετάφρενον 10.29; σάκος 11.527; τεῖχος 12.5; ὁδὸς εὐρυτέρη 23.427; εὐρὺν ἀγῶνα (see. ἀγών); κατά, ἀνά, μετὰ στρατὸν εὐρὺν Ἀχαιῶν, 1.229, 384, 478: frequently in _Epic dialect_ and Lyric poetry, rare in Trag. (except in Lyric poetry)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; in iambic trimeters, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Fragmenta” 921; ποιεῖν τὸν δῆμον εὐρὺν καὶ στενόν 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Equites” 720 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; not common in Prose (never in Papyri), εὐ. τάφρος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.178 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; κόθορνοι εὐρύτατοι <b>loose</b> boots, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] 6.125; οἰκίαι 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 4.5.25; οὔτ᾽ εὐρεῖα οὔτε στενὴ διαφυγή 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 737a \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; φλέβες εὐρύτεραι, opposed to λεπτότεραι, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Diogenes Apolloniates Philosophus 6, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Timaeus” 66d; πόροι 4th-3rd c.BC: Theophrastus Philosophus “de Causis Plantarum” 3.11.2; κατὰ στενότερα καὶ εὐρύτερα 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedo” 111d. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> <b>far-reaching, far-spread</b>, κλέος εὐρύ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 23.137; κληδών 4th-5th c.BC: Simonides Lyricus 84.6; εὐ. ἐλπίδες 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Epigrammata - PLG” 7. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> as <i>adverb</i>: the <i>neuter</i> εὐρύ is used as positive, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 13.24 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; compare εὐρυκρείων, εὐρυρέων: <i>comparative</i> εὐρυτέρως, ἔχειν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Lysistrata” 419 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]. (Sanskrit <i>urú</i>- 'wide', <i>comparative</i> <b>várīyān.</b>)","strongNumber":"G7564","accentedUnicode":"εὐρύς","shortDef":"broad","mediumDef":"broad","stepGloss":"broad","stepTransliteration":"eurus","count":0,"_step_Type":"word"}]}